    <text id="R13770675T">
        <front id="d2">
            <div1 type="summary" id="d3">
                <p>Union general Benjamin Kelley reports to West Virginia governor Arthur Boreman on
                    June, 1864, action in the Shenandoah Valley. Sigel reports that Unionist
                    citizens in the area reported seeing Confederate troops between Lynchburg and
                    Staunton.</p>
            </div1>
        </front>
        <body id="d4">
            <div1 type="letter" id="d5">
                <head>
                    <name type="recipient">Governor BOREMAN, Wheeling:</name>
                </head>
                <opener>
                    <dateline>
                        <date value="1864-06-25">June 25, 1864.</date>
                        <name type="place">CUMBERLAND,</name>
                    </dateline>
                    <salute/>
                </opener>
                <p>Maj. Hunter, at Beverly, reports his scouts just returned, who were ordered to
                    communicate with Gen. Hunter. They were compelled to return. Found a rebel force
                    of 1,500 holding Calf Pasture Valley, and 3,500 holding Buffalo Gap. Was
                    informed by Union citizens that Gen. Hunter was between Staunton and Lynchburg,
                    with Pickett and Breckinridge in his front. I am almost bare of force, and feel
                    great apprehension for the safety of West Virginia and the railroad.</p>
                <closer>
                    <salute/>
                    <signed>B. F. KELLEY,<lb/> Brig.-Gen.</signed>
                    <seg type="postscript">N. B.--Scout also reported heavy cannonading in the
                        direction of Lynchburg.</seg>
                </closer>
            </div1>
        </body>
    </text>
